## Purpose

Two carousel/scroll patterns exist in the project. This rule defines when to use each, how to implement them correctly, and which shared requirements apply to both.

---

## Pattern 1 — Horizontal Scroll Snap

**Use when**: Horizontally scrollable list of same-sized tiles (product cards, order cards, category chips).

**Reference implementation**: `client/components/walmart/NewArrivalsCarousel.tsx`

### When to use this pattern

- Tiles are the same size
- No auto-advance needed
- User controls scrolling manually (touch/mouse)
- More than ~4 tiles that won't all fit on screen

### CSS implementation

```css
/* Scroll container */
.carousel {
  display: flex;
  overflow-x: auto;
  scroll-snap-type: x mandatory;
  gap: var(--ld-primitive-scale-space-300, 12px);
  padding: var(--ld-primitive-scale-space-200, 8px) var(--ld-primitive-scale-space-400, 16px);
  /* Required: inner padding so card shadows don't get clipped */
}

/* Hide scrollbar visually */
.carousel {
  scrollbar-width: none; /* Firefox */
}
.carousel::-webkit-scrollbar {
  display: none; /* Chrome, Safari */
}

/* Individual tiles */
.tile {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  scroll-snap-align: start;
  width: 148px; /* Mobile */
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .tile { width: 180px; }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .tile { width: 200px; }
}
```

### Shadow clipping rule

If tiles have `box-shadow` elevation, add vertical padding **inside** the scroll container — never wrap with `overflow: hidden`:

```css
/* ✅ CORRECT — padding inside scroll container lets shadows breathe */
.carousel {
  padding: 8px 16px;
}

/* ❌ WRONG — clips shadows */
.carouselWrapper {
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

### No JS required

Basic scroll snap requires zero JavaScript. Only add JS if implementing scroll-to-index or keyboard arrow navigation.

