## Pattern 2 — Auto-Advance Full-Bleed Carousel

**Use when**: Full-width hero with auto-advancing slides and manual prev/next controls (promotional banners, hero campaigns).

**Reference implementation**: `client/components/walmart/JumpRightBackIn.tsx`

### When to use this pattern

- Slides are full-width (full-bleed)
- Content auto-advances on a timer
- User can manually prev/next through slides
- Each slide has distinct imagery and headline

### JS implementation

```tsx
const INTERVAL_MS = 5000;
const timerRef = useRef<ReturnType<typeof setInterval> | null>(null);

function startTimer() {
  timerRef.current = setInterval(() => {
    setActiveIndex((i) => (i + 1) % slides.length);
  }, INTERVAL_MS);
}

function stopTimer() {
  if (timerRef.current) clearInterval(timerRef.current);
}

// Start on mount, clear on unmount
useEffect(() => {
  startTimer();
  return stopTimer;
}, []);

// Pause on manual navigation, restart after user interaction
function goTo(index: number) {
  stopTimer();
  setActiveIndex(index);
  startTimer(); // restart after interaction
}
```

### Prev/Next controls

Always use `IconButton` with explicit `aria-label`:

```tsx
import { IconButton } from '@/components/ui/IconButton';
import { ChevronLeft, ChevronRight } from '@/components/icons';

<IconButton
  aria-label="Previous slide"
  icon={<ChevronLeft />}
  UNSAFE_className={styles.navButton}
  onClick={() => goTo((activeIndex - 1 + slides.length) % slides.length)}
/>
<IconButton
  aria-label="Next slide"
  icon={<ChevronRight />}
  UNSAFE_className={styles.navButton}
  onClick={() => goTo((activeIndex + 1) % slides.length)}
/>
```

`UNSAFE_className` is acceptable here to apply circular button styling to `IconButton` — this is one of the approved uses.

### Slide data pattern

Each slide object should include an `objectPosition` for image focal point control, and optionally `headlineParts` for multi-line headlines:

```ts
interface CarouselSlide {
  id: string;
  image: string;
  alt: string;
  objectPosition?: string;       // e.g. 'center top', '30% 50%'
  headline?: string;             // Single-line headline
  headlineParts?: string[];      // Multi-line headline (renders each part in <span>)
  ctaLabel?: string;
  ctaHref?: string;
}
```

### Multi-line headline rendering

Use `headlineParts` instead of `\n` in strings. Render each part in a block `<span>`:

```tsx
{slide.headlineParts
  ? slide.headlineParts.map((part, i) => (
      <span key={i} style={{ display: 'block' }}>{part}</span>
    ))
  : slide.headline
}
```

### Dynamic image position

Apply `objectPosition` as an inline style because it is dynamic per slide:

```tsx
<img
  src={slide.image}
  alt={slide.alt}
  className={styles.slideImage}
  style={{ objectPosition: slide.objectPosition ?? 'center' }}
/>
```

This is one of the approved uses of inline styles — the value varies per data item and cannot be expressed in a CSS module.

